QL1_2_exp: The project creates new jobs available for people in community since they have a high motivation to conserve and develop the area. This projects provide a place for them that supports productivity and sustainability in economic growth. With the existence of new, recreational opportunities, people in community would have a better place and a job to provide satisfaction in a productive lifestyle that will work together to contribute in the development of the community.
QL2_3_exp: The community needs an efficient ways of transportation away from motorized transportations that lead to pollution.Supporting walking and biking is significant for health in the community because it will benefit people health and also prevents disruptive and  polluted motorized transportation. The project addresses a way to rehabilitate pathways, bikes-lanes,  and water models. Moreover, the plan reduces the number of parking lots for motorized vehicles to encourage the use of public and non-motorized transportation. It also designs good paths for walking across a community park and biking lanes around the whole city to ensure a better life in terms of transportation use that fosters healthy community.
QL3_2_exp: The new plan respects the community values and takes into account their perspectives, needs and concern because the overall purpose of this project is to make the community a better place for its members to live. However, it the same time project members carefully examines these proposed plans and tries to asset them. For instance, members of the project tries to communicate with members of the community to make sure a specific plan to enhance their place is not going to negatively impact their values, ethics and beliefs. A satisfied community will be productive, collaborative and more willing to help us developing and restoring their area. They have a better knowledge and experience in their own place.
QL3_3_exp: The plans ensure a n overall net benefit for community members to ensure developing public spaces that meets the standards of moderately high-quality life. Public education facility will increase awareness, productivity, knowledge and it will enhance the community awareness towards the environment. Athletic fields, areas to study, parks to increase beauty and encourage walking are important to form a livable community.
NW1_2_exp: Providing buffer zones and complete protection of water bodies and natural elements is significant to ensure an effective plan for long-term. To prevent the damage from natural disasters, this plan can provide a safe community for the upcoming generations.
NW2_3_exp: The projects intends to incorporate and employ the use of monitoring water systems in order prevent surface and groundwater contamination. Water is valuable resource for life, and it is becoming a world issue. It is important to simulate education systems that prepare students in the community to work hard to keep their water safe and clean by improving projects that improve the quality of monitoring systems.
NW3_4_exp: The project maintains four ecosystem functions in the community by improving hydrologic cycle connection for streams, water quality from monitoring systems, supporting a habitat for aquatic and riparian species, and restoring sediment transport. The ecosystem is intended to maintain biological life and processes to provide community with clean and sustainable water resource.
CR1_1_exp: The plan takes into account the importance of conserving a clean environment. The emissions of carbon dioxide are managed and reduced to 100% reduction. The use of renewable and sustainable energy is supported by encouraging the use of non-motorized transportation and increasing community's awareness of the risks associated with emissions of gasses. Using filters to prevent dioxide to reach the environment, and fostering the use of environmentally-friendly methods are two main ways to approach this criteria. As a result, this will minimize the costs of cleaning pollution and reducing number of people with diseases that related to the emission of these gases.
CR2_2_exp: The project intends to create and enhance an understanding of the long-term risks, so that future plans are expected to deal with this problem of risks more in depth. The main focus now is to ensure the quality of sustainable, productive and livable community.

QL1_2_exp: Trails will be added to the park.  Trails need to be build and then upkept, which requires labor.  Additionally, having trails will increase the sales of the food and outdoor equipment stores in town, also trails may attract people from other towns to come to this town, increasing the sales of the restaurants in town and potentially create new jobs
QL2_3_exp: All of the trails in the park will be bike-friendly.  All of the different sites in the park will be connected by the trails. Using this input, the land is cleaned and the certain views are rebuilt.  Specific locations such at the viewing mound include paths but otherwise leave the land in its neutral state.

A playground and water access for recreational activities are included to encourage people to participate in recreational activities at the park
NW1_2_exp: There will be a buffer of plants at that allow nothing to be closer than 300 ft of the water (except a path for public access).  No pollutants will be able to reach the body of water.  There will be restrictions about the kinds of things people can bring to the water (aka no motorized vehicles, certain beverages, no dumping)
NW2_3_exp: The stream and the larger body of water will be monitored for levels of pollutants.  All of the structures in the park will have minimal pollutants that could leak to the ground.  Each structure and/or locations of the park will have plans in case of a leak. The brown land will be cleaned of pollutants.
NW3_4_exp: The park will maintain the stream habitat by removing any obstructions and by cleaning the brown land around the stream.  The flood plain water sources are restored back to normal.  Water quality will be monitored and maintained.
CR1_1_exp: The solar powered lights will make sure the lights do not require any extra energy.  Some of the energy may even be able to be sold back to the power grid on some days.  The walking/biking access will reduce the cars.  Solar panels will power all of the buildings in the park
CR2_2_exp: The plants added to the park will be indigenous but also able to withstand changing temperatures.  The community and its government will be consulted to make sure that everything the park will need to keep running can be found in the town now and in the future. The potential risks of the infrastructure will be evaluated and there is a financial plan in place in case of emergency

QL1_2_exp: The mentioned steps taken help improve the existing infrastructure, and also beautify the area further. This favors the overall social, economic and general development of the region surrounding it. The city basically becomes a more popular place in all these terms and becomes the center of new businesses and industries.

NW3_4_exp: While the overall natural surroundings that encompass the land and water vegetation can be protected from harm, it is important to look at the two environments together as an ecosystem of living organisms and abiotic components which work together to maintain the balance of the natural environment.
CR1_1_exp: The amount of air pollution can be significantly reduced by reducing the amount of greenhouse gas emissions. Also, a complete life-cycle carbon assessment in the region can be carried out to significantly reduce and monitor the amount of carbon emissions in the city. Encouraging the use of renewable energy can also help achieve this goal.
CR2_2_exp: In order for the long term development of the city to be achieved, the measure taken in this direction like documenting the potential traps and vulnerabilities  and their associated potential costs and risks helps improve the overall infrastructure of the area. This makes the community more resilient to any possible adverse situations in the future.

QL1_2_exp: The project is given enhanced rating since the project enhances the capabilities of the left out space by making it into something productive for the general public. QL3_2_exp: The project incorporates all the points discussed in the earlier paragraphs. QL3_3_exp: The project is meant to repair old spaces and renovate it to make it more productive. There would be cycle stands and food paths made for the use of the general public. Apart from that benches would be constructed for the people to sit on in the park.

QL1_2_exp: This project provides the community with a new jewel. The wetlands now serve as a place for activities like running, biking, and walking with family and friends. NW3_4_exp: The created marsh habitat will serve to restore the ecosystem and help it thrive. CR1_1_exp: The conversion from Light Industrial to an Open Space environment provides the team with an easier task in avoiding dangerous emissions. CR2_2_exp: Sluice gates and end caps help to drive up productivity and cut down cost by dividing the wetland into three independent cells. This precautionary action allows for option of altering the state of one cell based on water levels and availability. QL1_2_exp: This question primarily deals with the creation of jobs during the project and as a consequence of it, but also considers how the project will improve the overall appeal and socioeconomic health of the area.  Unfortunately, a park fails to create any sustainable jobs beyond those needed to build it and maintain it.  While it does improve the area and meet criteria A and D, it fails in the ways previously stated and thus fails B and C.  Therefore, it can only meet the category of improved.  Creation of a wild-life center could meet such requirements, but such a move may not be economical in comparison to its cost.
QL2_3_exp: The project meets requirement A as it is in close proximity to the main hub of town, allowing for easy access for locals.  The project meets part B as it provides a parking lot for people to use other modes of transportation.  Part C and D can be meet with the construction of quality walking and biking paths for people to use.  Part E can be meet if there is in fact public modes of transportation, but as none are mentioned in the plans, it can only be an assumption.  This part of the project with the creation of the pathway system would be of significant cost, so it would be advisable to meet criteria E or F if possible to perhaps receive additional public funding or support.
QL3_2_exp: It would be possible for the project team to meet the requirements of the the Restorative category, but it would be at significant cost and effort.  To meet such requirements, one would have to extensively work alongside the town to repair and protect the floodplain and wetland features.  It would also require working with the local government to draw up new ordnance protecting such features, a time-consuming ordeal.
QL3_3_exp: This question revolves around if the project improves the community through the establishment or restoration of public space with local agency approval.  It would be possible to completely restore the under-used park and brownfield, restoring both decrepit public area and converting developed private land to public land.   Creating athletic areas, walking trails, parks, and an amphitheater would drastically improve the public space.
NW1_2_exp: By establishing a 200 ft buffer while preserving the lands inside the buffer, it would be possible for the project to proceed as shown on the plans without significant disruption of the established plans of the amphitheater or parking areas.  It would be possible to gt a higher rating at increased cost and alteration of the plans, but this more comes down to budget and desire to change the size of other projects for the wetlands area.
NW2_3_exp: This one again falls to budget, as a complete monitoring and restoration of the area is possible.  The question revolves around the level of monitoring, cleanup ability, and prevention able to be undertaken.  By undertaking significant measures to protect and restore the flood lands, much of this is already done.  Cleaning up the brown zone will also significantly reduce the possibility of future water contamination.
NW3_4_exp: or this project, it would not be significantly difficult to meet at least three out of the four criteria, with the three being maintaining water quality, preventing loss of sediment, and maintaining habitats.  Connecting existing water systems would be more expensive and difficult, but taking proper precautions when dealing with the wet lands should allow the project to meet the three listed without significant cost.
CR1_1_exp: While a carbon assessment could be drawn up for this project, how a group could go about reducing such emissions is limited.  Rather then adjusting how a building is build or its emissions produced, much of the infrastructure being built are pathways and parking lots, leaving little room for improvement.
CR2_2_exp: For this project, it would likely be in the best interests of all parties involved for it to be in the restorative category.  The state of Alabama frequently deals with natural disasters such as hurricanes and tornadoes, and a project which is not prepared to counter or at least mitigate the damage of such an event could be completely undone by such an event.  It may be costly in the short run, but it would be even more costly to have to completely redo the project in the event of it being completely destroyed.

QL1_2_exp: By rebuilding the area struck by the tornado with new businesses, economic growth could come about, which would offset the costs in the long run of making everything go green. This increased business sector, will increase the wealth of small business owners, and invite lots of tourists to their small town.(A B C D E)
QL2_3_exp: Due to everyhting being destroyed in main street, it would be best to make only walking paths, bike path, and single lane roads where if you wanted to park you have to pay at a meter, whereas if you park further away from main street, and walk you can successfully prevent further pollution from car runoff from going into the park's nature life. Also, if both main street and the park are very close together, nearly all transportation can be done by walking or biking.
QL3_2_exp: Since the physical community has been wrecked, it'll be much easier to work with the locals and the lawmakers to come up with a plan that reflects the values and characteristics of a particular town/city.  In this case, since the town is pretty small, my team can easily meet with everyone at town hall meetings.
QL3_3_exp: In the main street, the public space in improved with beautiful shrubbery and plants that also serve as a garden and buffer to car pollution. Whereas the park, has walking and biking paths rather than charged car paths to help cut down on more pollution problems. Also, with the plants surrounding the park and the main street, runoff pollution can be minimized. By preventing pollution, we can also save the local wildlife by making profitable animal viewing tours in nature.
NW1_2_exp: Create a buffer from the town and the park about 200 feet away if when researched thoroughly that a wetland exists near the site, which is highly unlikely in the fact that this is a tornado fearing land. However the road pollution run off will be monitored and regulated with heavy shrubbery and plants to help buffer the wildlife.
NW2_3_exp: I don't believe that water pollution is the main problem here, because the site is not very close to a water source, so only runoff from cars would possible affect the groundwater, if it is not filtered enough by the shrubs put into the aesthetics design.
NW3_4_exp: Again, since my group is not focused on wetlands, we don't need to worry about it, and the runoff water is being solved with the addition of plants.
CR1_1_exp: Since, the use of cars will still be allowed around the sites, emission can not be entirely diminished, however it can be reduced by having people pay for their cars every time they need to park.
CR2_2_exp: Since the sites are highly susceptible to tornado damage, it would be wise to build with materials that are either very cheap to replace, meaning they are not eco-friendly, or build with heartier materials that may cost a fortune at first, until all of the businesses can start raking in money. Therefore, it would be very important for the team to talk with the people and vote on what they want after several ideas are pitched.

QL1_2_exp: The rebuilt city will include new businesses right away with the hope that new business investors will be attracted to the area as well as tourists and local visitors. Families may also want to move to the area which will further increase business investment.
QL2_3_exp: The project should include alternative means of transportation that helps reduce pollution while also encouraging business growth revolving around alternative transportation. NW1_2_exp: Measures should be taken to protect the local environment and ecosystem to prevent over-urbanization that destroys the local ecosystem. There also has to be additional measures taken to try to reduce the impact of future tornadoes such as setting a height limit for the buildings.

NW3_4_exp: The local rivers that run right through the city as well as the river that runs along the east side of the city should be protected. The rivers provide a nice scenic view for visitors and residents of the city as well as serve as a source of water for those people. The ecosystems surrounding the rivers can be converted into parks and nature preservation regions.
CR1_1_exp: Using more public, alternative transportation methods should help reduce the carbon footprint left behind by car emissions. The costs associated with reducing the gas emissions, however, is not worth the relatively small usage reduction.
CR2_2_exp: This is the ultimate goal of all restoration projects, especially infrastructure rebuilding. Avoiding long-term costs is essential for successful projects to exist. Measures to reduce the impact of future tornadoes will play a major role in fulfilling this requirement. The other requirements will all help contribute to this one as well.

QL1_2_exp: The brownfield was turned into green space for the purpose of community recreation. QL1_2_exp:
Four score and seven years ago our fathers brought forth on this continent, a new nation, conceived in Liberty, and dedicated to the proposition that all men are created equal. Now we are engaged in a great civil war, testing whether that nation, or any nation so conceived and so dedicated, can long endure. We are met on a great battle-field of that war. We have come to dedicate a portion of that field, as a final resting place for those who here gave their lives that that nation might live. It is altogether fitting and proper that we should do this.

But, in a larger sense, we can not dedicate -- we can not consecrate -- we can not hallow -- this ground. The brave men, living and dead, who struggled here, have consecrated it, far above our poor power to add or detract. The world will little note, nor long remember what we say here, but it can never forget what they did here.

QL1_2_exp: One way to help support and stimulate sustainable growth and development in the community would be to hire different people from within the community to help rebuild it. They could start by rebuilding small companies, that could then further hire more people, to help create more jobs for the citizens. They could also work together as a community to help create and design new buildings that look better than the previous ones in order to increase the attractiveness of the community.
QL2_3_exp: In order to help reduce congestion, the people of the town could create a central location where the public transit is located. There could also be more bike paths created to promote citizens to ride their bikes. There could also be more walking paths to help reduce the amount of people that drive their cars and cause congestion.
QL3_2_exp: In order to help successfully maintain the attitude of the town, the townspeople must be consulted. The engineers reconstructing this town must speak with people like the mayor of the town, or conduct a survey about important concepts of the town that they feel it is very important to maintain when deciding what steps to take in reconstructing the town.
QL3_3_exp: In order to do this successfully, some businesses may have to be compromised. Instead of constructing many buildings, there will have to be land conserved. There could also be restored hiking trails or bike paths for different civilians to take. Parks could also be reconstructed, and there is also an opportunity to make them better than before.
NW1_2_exp: A VSPZ with a 300-foot buffer would need to be added in order to maximize the protection and buffer of these areas. The other areas would also need to be restored and protected in order to achieve this goal. This can be done through helping to restore these areas and then establishing guidelines and rules in order to protect them.
NW2_3_exp: In order to achieve this goal, there would need to be environmental changes. Pollution would have to decrease and pollutants would need to be kept out of the water. This could be done through implementing different water preservation techniques. Designers need to identify the pollutants and discover a way to keep them out of the water.
NW3_4_exp: In order to achieve this goal, engineers must restore and preserve the four ecosystem functions including streams, wetlands, water bodies, and their riparian areas. this can be done through restoring these ecosystem functions through events such as fundraisers to earn money in order to help restore these.
CR1_1_exp: After the conclusion of this test, practically, it would be very difficult to have a 100% reduction of carbon use. Therefore, a practical goal to have would be to reduce carbon use by at least 40% which would still be a significant decrease.
CR2_2_exp: While not every disaster can be planned for, the most likely problems to occur can be. Therefore, designers would need to meet with the community official and discuss what they most likely disasters could be and need to establish systems and buildings to prevent complete destruction if a disaster occurs.

QL1_2_exp: The transformation of the maintenance yard into a  community park will repair broken infrastructure and improve the general appearance of the community.  It will also increase livability by giving community members a place to gather outside.  The creation of this park will increase community development and provide jobs.
QL2_3_exp: The constructed works, bike path, sidewalks, and bike lanes promote alternatives to non motorized transportation.  A traffic study was conducted and an appropriate number of parking spots were created that will encourage the use of non motor transportation.  This will also reduce congestion by limiting the number of cars that will be present in the environment due to limitations on parking.
QL3_2_exp: Important elements of the community's visual character were identified in the planning stages.  Barriers, like the dilapidated homes, were removed, which allowed the visual character of the community to be improved.  The project restored lost character withing in the community by improving the views in the neighborhood.
QL3_3_exp: Existing public use facilities were restored.  Through the restoration, the discharge of pollutants from urban run-off is also reduced, improving the natural environment.  Overall, the enhanced public space increases the livability of the community and is accepted by the community and appropriate agencies.
NW1_2_exp: The project is not located on a sight that is within the specified distance of an aquatic resource.  The degraded buffer zone was restored by stabilizing the stream channel/shoreline.  The wetland was vegetated with plants native to the community.  The change of the land use designation provided the wetland with added protection that it will remain as a wetland.
NW2_3_exp: The project prevents future contamination from the Brownfield site by creating an impermeable layer and using land control measures.  Potentially polluting materials are contained through the collection of dry weather runoff and through the creation of the geosynthetic clay liner.  The measures used restore a previously contaminated area.
NW3_4_exp: The project enhances water quality by using the storm water runoff as a resource to sustain the wetland.  The project also improves the ecosystem by protecting waterways by diverting the urban runoff to a place where it can be as a restorative measure rather than a pollutant.  The marsh habitat in the urban area allows for the urban storm water to be used to restore the environment rather than harm it.
CR1_1_exp: The project would be Net Carbon Negative, meaning that the project would use more carbon from the air than it would generate.  The team used a carbon life style assessment to determine how to make the project carbon negative.  The project also used many forms of renewable energy in the design of the project.
CR2_2_exp: The project team assessed potential vulnerabilities and addressed them by developing sluice gates and end caps for orficies which allows fr the wetland to be reconfigured if needed.  The project also eliminates infrastructure traps through the use of multiple wetland cells which allows the wetland configuration to change with the environment.

QL1_2_exp: Analyses showing new jobs that will be created from design, construction, and operation of the project. Report showing how the completed project expands the capacity or increases the quality of operating, recreational or cultural capacity. Confirmation of the report results by references to official community plans, goals, needs assessments, minutes of meetings, or letters from community leaders, or decision makers.
QL2_3_exp: Location and design drawings showing proximity and accessibility to transportation facilities. Degree of convenience and accessibility. Location and design drawings showing parking availability in and around the constructed works. Parking spaces available relative to expected use of the constructed works and availability of alternative transportation. Comparisons to other parking restricted facilities and infrastructure.
QL3_2_exp: Plans, drawings, and reports identifying important elements of the site character including landform or levels, views, natural landscape features, materials, planting, style/detailing, scale, and landscape/townscape pattern.
QL3_3_exp: Studies and assessments of the impact of the project on existing public space. Design documents describing any new public space developed as part of the project. Reports documenting determination of benefits, improvements, negative impacts. Reports documenting determination of risks to public health and safety.
NW1_2_exp: Documentation that the proposed site neither contains nor is within the specified distance of a wetland, vernal pool, shoreline, waterbody, or other aquatic resource. A site plan showing the final site design, the boundaries of the VSPZ, and the minimal VSPZ depth calculated as the shortest point between the VSPZ boundary and the identified wetland, waterbody, or shoreline.
NW2_3_exp:
Documentation of hydrogeologic delineation studies, taking into consideration the complexity of the aquifers. (Note that delineation already may have been done by local authorities.)
For projects situated in areas where the groundwater is used as a source or drinking water, documentation of wellhead protection plans and other requirements including establishing wellhead protection areas.
NW3_4_exp:
For streams, rivers, and lakes, documentation showing how the waterway is connected or proposed to be connected to its riparian floodplain at a 6-month to 2-year frequency flow event.

QL1_2_exp: This project will create a place for people to exercise and socialize, as well as build communities. It is also an attractive area, raising the value of property and therefore business utility nearby.

A: Workers can be hired to maintain the landscape and conduct operations such as pruning plants or mowing the lawn.
B: A basketball court can be added to the park and workers can be hired to actively clean and maintain the basketball structures, which will draw kids and adults alike to participate in recreational activities.
C: People can work out or walk in the park, reducing congestion in local gyms, streets, or areas for exercise.
QL2_3_exp: There will only be one parking lot to encourage alternate means of transportation. There will be well lit and sheltered bus stops as well as bike racks surrounding the perimeter such that easy access and drop off is possible. There will be ample walkways that provide access to each bike rack and bus stop, and a trolley will be built for access around the park.
QL3_2_exp: Old buildings near the park will be painted with murals or trees will be planted to make more visibly attractive. The park itself will have grass planted throughout and there will be gardens alongside some walkways for visual pleasure. There will be strict fines, as indicated by signs near the entrances to the park for littering or walking on plants or in areas that are meant for viewing.
QL3_3_exp: The park will include recreation parks and fields for sports, as well as gardens and landscapes for viewing pleasure. There will be plenty of trees such that viewers can observe local wildlife like birds and squirrels. Monthly meetings will be held open to all locals to vote on issues on new recreation activities or fields to be put towards different uses.
NW1_2_exp: The park will not be built within 300 feet of any nature buffer zones and the services will not adversely affect any soil or vegetation. There will be compost beens for degradable food products that can be used to replenish local plant-life, and revenue from the billboards or donations will be put towards planting trees and improving the ecosystem.
NW2_3_exp: The park will be developed with natural materials like wood so that in the event of destruction there will not be hard to remove materials from the local environment. Materials for the parks operation will be stored in elevated wooden containers so that flooding and water runoff will not carry off the materials.
NW3_4_exp: Sediment will be removed by the park maintenance crews. Water filtration systems built with sediment like sand will purify the water runoff. There will be land barriers built around any bodies of water like small ponds that prevent destructive materials from entering.
CR1_1_exp: The park will not contain any machines and will forbid people from riding vehicles like motorcycles or mopeds that run on fuel. There will be no food vendors that cook food, only a farmers market type set up that will serve premade and fresh food. The open land and space will limit the green house gas emission for the surrounding area.
CR2_2_exp: The park's irrigation systems for plants and gardens will be separated so that each can be maintained and repaired without cutting off the others. The recreation fields and/or courts will be routinely checked for destruction, and in the event that they are destroyed they will be converted to pond or a garden that does not allow human access.

QL1_2_exp: This project will create a place for people to exercise and socialize, as well as build communities. It is also an attractive area, raising the value of property and therefore business utility nearby.
QL2_3_exp: A park-like area like this has many opportunities for modes of transportation; for instance, a bus stop could be placed on the property. There could also be areas to lock bikes or rent bikes, and paths through it that people could use rather than drive their own cars.
QL3_2_exp: A park is a very simple project; it likely will not negatively impact the community.
QL3_3_exp: Since this is a natural area, there are many ways to improve the space. There could be areas like a nature center or hiking trails so that the public can get in contact with nature. Additionally, pavilions and the like could be made and the public could rent them to bring in revenue and support future development.
NW1_2_exp: As this is a park, it makes sense that natural buffer zones are included to help conserve nature nearby. A floodplain and wetlands are part of the area, and buffer zones will greatly increase the healthiness of this area especially in regard to water and animal conservation.
NW2_3_exp: The park will have few, if any, water resources besides natural ones, making this unnecessary.
NW3_4_exp: Buffer areas are included above, so this part will not have a ton to add. Some areas should be sectioned off to protect from ecosystem disruptions.
CR1_1_exp: There will be very few greenhouse gas emissions, just as a function of it being a park, not something like a building that uses energy.
CR2_2_exp: In order to make this a safe area for the public and for native animals, dangerous areas should either be made safe or sectioned off. This could cost a lot, but will result in a much more environmentally-friendly site.

QL1_2_exp: The project team conducted an assessment of lighting needs and found only security lighting along the pedestrian walkways was needed.

The park could add recreational facilities to the area, such as sports fields and courts, which would add value to the park's recreational capacity. If the park creators or sponsors then sponsored recreational leagues, coaching jobs, referee positions, and other jobs would be created. They could even partner with a local school to allow for practice to be held there so that the school system doesn't have to build new fields as well.
QL2_3_exp: Paths can be built specifically for bikes that will connect areas around the park as efficiently as possible. The park can work with the local municipality to have a route that goes directly to some form of public transportation from local neighborhoods, including bike paths or lanes beyond the extent of the park.
QL3_2_exp: The project managers should consult local leaders and community members on any concerns they may have about the finished project of the park and make sure that none of those things end up in the final project.
QL3_3_exp: As I addressed in the first part, recreational courts and a facility can be built for community or school use. The final product will be a park, adding value in that way to the community in the form of space. Another thing that could be done is convert an existing building, if there is one, into a local market where community members can make money, or buy goods that friends and neighbors may make. This would add an income for some people, and possibly provide a less expensive source of food/goods for others.
NW1_2_exp: The land can be properly graded so that water runs into a wetlands area in the center of the park. This will provide a detoxifying area for the water, as well as a place for runoff to go and be stored/infiltrate into the ground. The park should be far from existing wetlands area in order to preserve them.
NW2_3_exp: A wetlands area, as discussed, is a good way to remove toxins before the water infiltrates into the ground. This will help keep water clean. The quality of the water can be monitored to determine how efficiently the area is working. Reed and cattails work well in stagnant water and can remove pollutants at their roots when they take up water.
NW3_4_exp: If a stream runs through the park, re-grading the banks and planting trees can add to the health of the stream. If water flows more into the wetlands, it will reduce the high flow that is caused by rainy times.
CR1_1_exp: Planning ahead of time can reduce the time that machines are used in the construction of the park and buildings. This will limit the time that they are putting out emissions. Also, solar energy can be used for the recreational facility to limit emissions during the life of the project.
CR2_2_exp: Using as many existing buildings as possible will very easily reduce the large costs of building new structures. Assessing the land to do the least amount of grading is also an important consideration.

QL1_2_exp: The plan for this park would to make it self-sustainable. There would be solar panel powered lamp posts to provide natural light for the park, a play ground where children can play, and a wide area of natural grass for multi-purpose use. Overall this would increase the appeal of the city.
QL2_3_exp: The park should promote active and healthy lifestyles. It should be distanced from the pollution and hazards of motorized vehicles. Moreover, there will be designated bike paths and rental bikes that community members can use.
QL3_2_exp: Certain values that the community sees important will be conserved and portrayed in the park. For example, a motto or common theme could be incorporated into the park.
QL3_3_exp: The restoration of this park should have minimal adverse affects to the community. The basic objective is to make the changes without making a significant negative impact on the environment.
NW1_2_exp: Ensuring that there is a safe distance between the wetlands and any possible construction is essential to maintaining a clean environment. This would require to plan the project to be a considerable distance away.
NW2_3_exp: To ensure that there will be minimal to no surface or groundwater contamination will require the evaluation of any possible factors that may lead to this problem. Once the problem is located, it will be easier to fine a solution to minimize the likelihood of it happening.
NW3_4_exp: To maintain and restore the functions of the streams and water bodies will require the aid of those who specialize in the field. They will help to deal with certain aspects of the issue.
CR1_1_exp: Following a detailed analysis of the carbon cycle assessment, the task would be reducing it by 10%. This would be completed by locating areas where there can be a decrease in usage without compromising use.
CR2_2_exp: In the long run, it is essential that the park will be able to maintain its purpose with the changing environment. This would result in the constant analysis of the environment to locate any changes.

QL1_2_exp: The new improvements to the visual appearance of the town will greatly increase the amount of tourism that goes on resulting in a relatively large increase in economic growth. NW2_3_exp: Put up signs to warn the public of their close proximity to the body of water and enforce no littering and no dumping rules. NW3_4_exp: If there is a creek make sure that you direct rain water and parking lot runoff  so that streams are less likely to be damaged by pollution. CR1_1_exp: To reduce the impact on the climate require emission filters on machines to prevent less toxins from being released into the air. Making the plans able to be changed on the fly would also be useful to the overall project cost.
